# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: livestock-monitoring
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] A wide range of other species, such as horse, water buffalo, llama, rabbit, and guinea pig, are used as livestock in some parts of the world.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Insect farming, as well as aquaculture of fish, molluscs, and crustaceans, is widespread.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Modern animal husbandry relies on production systems adapted to the available land.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Subsistence farming is being superseded by intensive animal farming in the more developed parts of the world, where, for example, beef cattle are kept in high-density feedlots, and thousands of chickens may be raised in broiler houses or batteries.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] On poorer soil, such as in uplands, animals are often kept more extensively and may be allowed to roam widely, foraging for themselves.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Animal agriculture at modern scale drives climate change, ocean acidification, and biodiversity loss.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Most livestock are herbivores, except (among the most commonly-kept species) for pigs and chickens, which are omnivores.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Ruminants like cattle and sheep are adapted to feed on grass; they can forage outdoors or may be fed entirely or in part on rations richer in energy and protein, such as pelleted cereals.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Pigs and poultry cannot digest the cellulose in forage and require other high-protein foods.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Farmers and ranchers who raise livestock are considered to practice *animal husbandry*.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The domestication of livestock was driven by the need to have food on hand when hunting was unproductive.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The desirable characteristics of a domestic animal are that it should be useful to the domesticator, should be able to thrive in their company, should breed freely, and be easy to tend.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Domestication was not a single event, but a process repeated at various periods in different places.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Sheep and goats were the animals that accompanied the nomads in the Middle East, while cattle and pigs were associated with more settled communities.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The first wild animal to be domesticated was the dog.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Half-wild dogs, perhaps starting with young individuals, may have been tolerated as scavengers and killers of vermin, and, being naturally pack hunters, were predisposed to become part of the human pack and join in the hunt.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Prey animals, sheep, goats, pigs, and cattle, were progressively domesticated early in the history of agriculture.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Pigs were domesticated in the Near East between 8,500 and 8000 BC, sheep and goats in or near the Fertile Crescent about 8,500 BC, and cattle from wild aurochs in the areas of modern Turkey and Pakistan around 8,500 BC.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] A cow was a great advantage to a villager as she produced more milk than her calf needed, and her strength could be put to use as a working animal, pulling a plough to increase production of crops, and drawing a sledge, and later a cart, to bring the produce home from the field.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Draught animals were first used about 4,000 BC in the Middle East, increasing agricultural production immeasurably.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] In southern Asia, the elephant was domesticated by 6,000 BC.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Fossilised chicken bones dated to 5040 BC have been found in northeastern China, far from where their wild ancestors lived in the jungles of tropical Asia, but archaeologists believe that the original purpose of domestication was for the sport of cockfighting.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Meanwhile, in South America, the llama and the alpaca had been domesticated, probably before 3,000 BC, as beasts of burden and for their wool.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Neither was strong enough to pull a plough, which limited the development of agriculture in the New World.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Horses occur naturally on the steppes of Central Asia, and their domestication began around 3,000 BC in the Black Sea and Caspian Sea region.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Although horses were originally seen as a source of meat, their use as pack animals and for riding followed.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Around the same time, the wild ass was being tamed in Egypt.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Camels were domesticated soon after this, with the Bactrian camel in Mongolia and the Arabian camel becoming beasts of burden.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] By 1000 BC, caravans of Arabian camels were linking India with Mesopotamia and the Mediterranean.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] In ancient Egypt, cattle were the most important livestock, and sheep, goats, and pigs were also kept; poultry including ducks, geese, and pigeons were captured in nets and bred on farms, where they were force-fed with dough to fatten them.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The Nile provided a plentiful source of fish.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Honey bees were domesticated from at least the Old Kingdom, providing both honey and wax.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] In ancient Rome, all the livestock known in ancient Egypt were available.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] In addition, rabbits were domesticated for food by the first century BC.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] To help flush them out from their burrows, the polecat was domesticated as the ferret, its use described by Pliny the Elder.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] In northern Europe, agriculture, including animal husbandry, declined after the collapse of the Roman Empire.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Some aspects, such as the herding of animals, continued throughout the period.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] By the 11th century, the economy had recovered, and the countryside was again productive.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Woodland for [feeding] 70 pigs." The improvements of animal husbandry in the medieval period in Europe went hand in hand with other developments.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Improvements to the plough allowed the soil to be tilled to a greater depth.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Horses took over from oxen as the main providers of traction, new ideas on crop rotation were developed, and the growing of crops for winter fodder gained ground.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Peas, beans, and vetches became common; they increased soil fertility through nitrogen fixation, allowing more livestock to be kept.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The exploration and colonisation of North and South America resulted in the introduction of crops such as maize, potatoes, sweet potatoes, and manioc into Europe.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] At the same time, the principal Old World livestock – cattle, horses, sheep, and goats – were introduced into the New World for the first time along with wheat, barley, rice, and turnips.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Selective breeding for desired traits was established as a scientific practice by Robert Bakewell during the British Agricultural Revolution in the 18th century.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] One of his most important breeding programs was with sheep.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Using native stock, he was able to quickly select for large, yet fine-boned sheep, with long, lustrous wool.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The Lincoln Longwool was improved by Bakewell, and, in turn, the Lincoln was used to develop the subsequent breed, the New (or Dishley) Leicester.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] It was hornless and had a square, meaty body with straight top lines.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] These sheep were exported widely and have contributed to numerous modern breeds.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Under his influence, English farmers began to breed cattle primarily for beef.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Long-horned heifers were crossed with the Westmoreland bull to create the Dishley Longhorn.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The semi-natural, unfertilised pastures formed by traditional agricultural methods in Europe were managed by grazing and mowing.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] As the ecological impact of this land management strategy is similar to that of natural disturbances such as grazing and wildfire, this agricultural system shares many beneficial characteristics with a natural habitat, including promoting biodiversity.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] This strategy is declining in Europe today due to intensified agriculture.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The mechanized and chemical methods used are causing biodiversity to decline.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Traditionally, animal husbandry was part of the subsistence farmer's way of life, producing not only the food needed by the family but also the fuel, fertiliser, clothing, transport, and draught power.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Killing the animal for food was a secondary consideration; wherever possible its products such as wool, eggs, milk and blood (by the Maasai) were harvested while the animal was still alive.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] In the traditional system of transhumance, people and livestock moved seasonally between fixed summer and winter pastures; in montane regions the summer pasture was up in the mountains, the winter pasture in the valleys.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Animals can be kept extensively or intensively.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Extensive systems involve animals roaming at will, or under the supervision of a herdsman, often for their protection from predators.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Ranching in the Western United States involves large herds of cattle grazing widely over public and private lands.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Similar cattle stations are found in South America, Australia, and other places with large areas of land and low rainfall.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Ranching systems have been used for sheep, deer, ostrich, emu, llama and alpaca.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] In the uplands of the United Kingdom, sheep are turned out on the fells in spring and graze the abundant mountain grasses untended, being brought to lower altitudes late in the year, with supplementary feeding being provided in winter.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] In rural locations, pigs and poultry can obtain much of their nutrition from scavenging, and in African communities, hens may live for months without being fed, and still produce one or two eggs a week.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] In between these two extremes are semi-intensive, often family-run farms where livestock graze outside for much of the year, silage or hay is made to cover the times of year when the grass stops growing, and fertiliser, feed, and other inputs are brought onto the farm from outside.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Animals used as livestock are predominantly herbivorous, the main exceptions being the pig and the chicken, which are omnivorous.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Herbivores can be divided into "concentrate selectors", which selectively feed on seeds, fruits, and highly nutritious young foliage; "grazers", which mainly feed on grass; and "intermediate feeders", which choose their diet from the full range of available plant material.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Cattle, sheep, goats, deer, and antelopes are ruminants; they digest food in two steps, chewing and swallowing in the normal way, and then regurgitating the semidigested cud to chew it again and thus extract the maximum possible food value.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The dietary needs of these animals are mostly met by eating grass.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Grasses grow from the base of the leaf-blade, enabling it to thrive even when heavily grazed or cut.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] In many climates, grass growth is seasonal, for example, in the temperate summer or tropical rainy season, so some areas of the crop are set aside to be cut and preserved, either as hay (dried grass), or as silage (fermented grass).
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Other forage crops are also grown and many of these, as well as crop residues, can be ensiled to fill the gap in the nutritional needs of livestock in the lean season.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Extensively reared animals may subsist entirely on forage, but more intensively kept livestock will require energy and protein-rich foods in addition.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Energy is mainly derived from cereals and cereal by-products, fats and oils, and sugar-rich foods, while protein may come from fish or meat meal, milk products, legumes, and other plant foods, often the by-products of vegetable oil extraction.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Pigs and poultry are non-ruminants and are unable to digest the cellulose in grass and other forages, so they are fed entirely on cereals and other high-energy foodstuffs.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The ingredients for the animals' rations can be grown on the farm or bought as pelleted or cubed compound foodstuffs, specially formulated for different classes of livestock, their growth stages, and their specific nutritional requirements.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Vitamins and minerals are added to balance the diet.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Farmed fish are usually fed pelleted food.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The breeding of farm animals seldom occurs spontaneously but is managed by farmers to encourage traits considered desirable.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] These include hardiness, fertility, docility, mothering abilities, fast growth rates, low feed consumption per unit of growth, better body proportions, higher yields, and better fibre qualities.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Undesirable traits such as health defects and aggressiveness are selected against.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Selective breeding has been responsible for significant productivity increases.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] For example, in 2007, a typical broiler chicken at eight weeks old was 4.8 times as heavy as a bird of similar age in 1957, while in the thirty years to 2007, the average milk yield of a dairy cow in the United States nearly doubled.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Good husbandry, proper feeding, and hygiene are the main contributors to animal health on the farm, bringing economic benefits through maximised production.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] When, despite these precautions, animals still become sick, they are treated with veterinary medicines, by the farmer and the veterinarian.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] In the European Union, when farmers treat their own animals, they are required to follow treatment guidelines and record the treatments given.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Animals are susceptible to many diseases and conditions that may affect their health.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Some, like classical swine fever and scrapie are specific to one type of stock, while others, like foot-and-mouth disease affect all cloven-hoofed animals.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Animals living under intensive conditions are prone to internal and external parasites; increasing numbers of sea lice are affecting farmed salmon in Scotland.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Reducing the parasite burdens of livestock results in increased productivity and profitability.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Where the condition is serious, governments impose regulations on imports and exports, the movement of stock, quarantine restrictions, and the reporting of suspected cases.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Vaccines are available against certain diseases, and antibiotics are widely used where appropriate.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] At one time, antibiotics were routinely added to certain compound foodstuffs to promote growth.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Still, this practice is now frowned on in many countries because of the risk that it may lead to antimicrobial resistance in livestock and in humans.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Governments are concerned with zoonoses, diseases that humans may acquire from animals.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Wild animal populations may harbour diseases that can affect domestic animals, which may acquire them as a result of insufficient biosecurity.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] An outbreak of Nipah virus in Malaysia in 1999 was traced back to pigs becoming ill after contact with fruit-eating flying foxes, their faeces and urine.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The pigs, in turn, passed the infection to humans.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Avian flu H5N1 is present in wild bird populations and can be carried large distances by migrating birds.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] This virus is easily transmissible to domestic poultry and to humans living in proximity to them.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Other infectious diseases affecting wild animals, farm animals and humans include rabies, leptospirosis, brucellosis, tuberculosis and trichinosis.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] There is no single universally agreed-upon definition of what species are considered livestock.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Widely recognized livestock types include cattle for beef and dairy, sheep, goats, pigs, and poultry.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Various other species are sometimes considered livestock, such as horses, while poultry birds are sometimes excluded.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] In some parts of the world, livestock includes species such as buffalo, and the South American camelids, the alpaca and llama.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Some authorities use much broader definitions to include fish in aquaculture, micro-livestock such as rabbits and rodents like guinea pigs, as well as insects from honey bees to crickets raised for human consumption.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Animals are raised for a wide variety of products, principally meat, wool, milk, and eggs, but also including tallow, isinglass, and rennet.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Animals are also kept for more specialised purposes, such as to produce vaccines and antiserum (containing antibodies) for medical use.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Where fodder or other crops are grown alongside animals, manure can serve as a fertiliser, returning minerals and organic matter to the soil in a semi-closed organic system.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Although all mammals produce milk to nourish their young, cows are predominantly used worldwide to produce milk and milk products for human consumption.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Other animals used to a lesser extent for this purpose include sheep, goats, camels, buffaloes, yaks, reindeer, horses, and donkeys.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] All these animals have been domesticated over the centuries, bred for desirable characteristics such as fecundity, productivity, docility, and the ability to thrive under prevailing conditions.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Whereas in the past cattle had multiple functions, modern dairy cow breeding has produced specialised Holstein Friesian-type animals that produce large quantities of milk economically.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Artificial insemination is widely available, allowing farmers to select for traits that suit their circumstances.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] In many communities, milk production is only part of the purpose of keeping an animal, which may also be used as a beast of burden or to draw a plough, or for the production of fibre, meat and leather, with the dung being used for fuel or for the improvement of soil fertility.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Sheep and goats may be favoured for dairy production in climates and conditions that do not suit dairy cows.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Meat, mainly from farmed animals, is a major source of dietary protein and essential nutrients around the world, averaging about 8% of human energy intake.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The actual types eaten depend on local preferences, availability, cost, and other factors, with cattle, sheep, pigs, and goats being the main species involved.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Cattle generally produce a single offspring annually which takes more than a year to mature; sheep and goats often have twins and these are ready for slaughter in less than a year; pigs are more prolific, producing more than one litter of up to about 11 piglets each year.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Horses, donkeys, deer, buffalo, llamas, alpacas, guanacos and vicunas are farmed for meat in various regions.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Some desirable traits of animals raised for meat include fecundity, hardiness, fast growth rate, ease of management, and high food conversion efficiency.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] About half of the world's meat is produced from animals grazing on open ranges or enclosed pastures; the other half is produced intensively in various factory-farming systems.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] These are mostly cows, pigs, or poultry, and are often reared indoors at high densities.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Poultry kept for their eggs and meat include chickens, turkeys, geese, and ducks.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The great majority of laying birds used for egg production are chickens.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The battery cages are arranged in long rows across multiple tiers, with external feeders, drinkers, and egg-collection facilities.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] This is the most labour-saving and economical method of egg production.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Still, it has been criticised on animal-welfare grounds because the birds are unable to exhibit their normal behaviours.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] In the developed world, the majority of poultry reared for meat is raised indoors in large sheds, with automated equipment and environmentally controlled conditions.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Chickens raised in this way are known as broilers, and genetic improvements have enabled them to reach slaughter weight within six or seven weeks of hatching.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Newly hatched chicks are confined to a small area and provided with supplementary heating.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Litter on the floor absorbs droppings, and the area it occupies expands as they grow.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Feed and water are supplied automatically, and the lighting is controlled.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The birds may be harvested on several occasions, or the entire shed may be cleared at once.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] A similar rearing system is usually used for turkeys, which are less hardy than chickens, take longer to reach maturity, and are often moved to separate fattening units to finish.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Ducks are particularly popular in Asia and Australia and can be killed at seven weeks under commercial conditions.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Aquaculture has been defined as "the farming of aquatic organisms, including fish, molluscs, crustaceans, and aquatic plants, and implies some form of intervention in the rearing process to enhance production, such as regular stocking, feeding, protection from predators, etc.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Farming also implies individual or corporate ownership of the stock being cultivated." In practice, it can take place in the sea or in freshwater, and be extensive or intensive.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Whole bays, lakes, or ponds may be devoted to aquaculture, or the farmed animal may be retained in cages (fish), artificial reefs, racks, or strings (shellfish).
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Fish and prawns can be cultivated in rice paddies, either arriving naturally or being introduced, and both crops can be harvested together.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Fish hatcheries provide larval and juvenile fish, crustaceans, and shellfish for use in aquaculture systems.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] When large enough, these are transferred to growing-on tanks and sold to fish farms for harvest.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Some species that are commonly raised in hatcheries include shrimps, prawns, salmon, tilapia, oysters and scallops.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Similar facilities can be used to raise species with conservation needs for release into the wild, or game fish for restocking waterways.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Important aspects of husbandry at these early stages include selection of breeding stock, control of water quality, and nutrition.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] In the wild, there is a high mortality rate at the nursery stage; farmers seek to minimise it while maximising growth rates.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Bees have been kept in hives since at least the First Dynasty of Egypt, five thousand years ago, and man had been harvesting honey from the wild long before that.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Fixed-comb hives are used in many parts of the world and are made from locally available materials.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] In more advanced economies, where modern strains of domestic bee have been selected for docility and productiveness, various designs of hive are used which enable the combs to be removed for processing and extraction of honey.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Quite apart from the honey and wax they produce, honey bees are important pollinators of crops and wild plants, and in many places hives are transported around the countryside to assist in pollination.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Sericulture, the rearing of silkworms, was first adopted by the Chinese during the Shang dynasty.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The only species farmed commercially is the domesticated silkmoth.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] When it spins its cocoon, each larva produces an exceedingly long, slender thread of silk.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The larvae feed on mulberry leaves, and in Europe, only one generation is typically raised each year because mulberry is a deciduous tree.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] In China, Korea, and Japan, however, two generations are normal, and in the tropics, multiple generations are expected.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Most silk production occurs in the Far East, with synthetic diets used to rear silkworms in Japan.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Insects form part of the human diet in many cultures.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] In Thailand, crickets are farmed for this purpose in the north of the country, and palm weevil larvae in the south.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The crickets are kept in pens, boxes, or drawers and fed on commercial pelleted poultry food, while the palm weevil larvae live on cabbage palm and sago palm trees, which limits their production to areas where these trees grow.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Another delicacy of this region is the bamboo caterpillar, and the best rearing and harvesting techniques in semi-natural habitats are being studied.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Animal husbandry has a significant impact on the world environment.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Both production and consumption of animal products have increased rapidly.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Since 1950, meat production has tripled, dairy production has doubled, and egg production has increased almost fourfold.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Meanwhile, meat consumption has nearly doubled worldwide.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Developing countries had a surge in meat consumption, particularly of monogastric livestock.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Animal husbandry drives climate change, ocean acidification, and biodiversity loss, and kills 60 billion animals annually.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] It uses between 20 and 33% of the world's fresh water, Livestock, and the production of feed for them, occupy about a third of the Earth's ice-free land.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Livestock production contributes to species extinction, desertification, and habitat destruction. and is the primary driver of the Holocene extinction.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Some 70% of the agricultural land and 30% of Earth's land surface is involved directly or indirectly in animal husbandry.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Habitat is destroyed by clearing forests and converting land to grow feed crops and for grazing, while predators and herbivores are frequently targeted because of a perceived threat to livestock profits; for example, animal husbandry causes up to 91% of the deforestation in the Amazon region.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] In addition, livestock produce greenhouse gases.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Cows produce some 570 million cubic metres of methane per day, that accounts for 35 to 40% of the overall methane emissions of the planet.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Further, livestock production is responsible for 65% of all human-related emissions of nitrous oxide.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Since the 18th century, people have become increasingly concerned about the welfare of farm animals.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Possible measures of welfare include longevity, behavior, physiology, reproduction, freedom from disease, and freedom from immunosuppression.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] An opposing view is that animals have rights, should not be regarded as property, are not necessary to use, and should never be used by humans.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Live export of animals has risen to meet increased global demand for livestock, such as in the Middle East.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Animal rights activists have objected to the long-distance transport of animals; one result was the banning of live exports from New Zealand in 2003.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Since the 18th century, the farmer John Bull has represented English national identity, first in John Arbuthnot's political satires, and soon afterwards in cartoons by James Gillray and others, including John Tenniel.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] He likes food, beer, dogs, horses, and country sports; he is practical, down-to-earth, and anti-intellectual.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Farm animals are widespread in children's books and songs; the reality of animal husbandry is often distorted, softened, or idealized, giving children an almost entirely fictitious account of farm life.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The books often depict happy animals free to roam in attractive countryside, a picture completely at odds with the realities of the impersonal, mechanized activities involved in modern intensive farming.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Pigs, for example, appear in several of Beatrix Potter's "little books", as Piglet in A.A.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Milne's Winnie the Pooh stories, and somewhat more darkly (with a hint of animals going to slaughter) as Babe in Dick King-Smith's *The Sheep-Pig*, and as Wilbur in E.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Pigs tend to be "bearers of cheerfulness, good humour and innocence".
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Many of these books are completely anthropomorphic, dressing farm animals in clothes and having them walk on two legs, live in houses, and perform human activities.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] The children's song "Old MacDonald Had a Farm" describes a farmer named MacDonald and the various animals he keeps, celebrating the noises they each make.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Many urban children experience animal husbandry for the first time at a petting farm; in Britain, some five million people a year visit a farm of some kind.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] This presents some risk of infection, especially if children handle animals and then fail to wash their hands; a strain of *E. coli* infected 93 people who had visited a British interactive farm in an outbreak in 2009.
[src:livestock-monitoring/animal-husbandry] Historic farms such as those in the United States offer farmstays and "a carefully curated version of farming to those willing to pay for it", sometimes giving visitors a romanticised image of a pastoral idyll from an unspecified time in the pre-industrial past.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] The milking process is the collection of tasks specifically devoted to extracting milk from an animal (rather than the broader field of dairy animal husbandry).
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] Maintaining milk yield during the lactation period (approximately 300 days) requires consistent milking intervals, usually twice daily and with maximum time spacing between milkings.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] In fact, all activities on the dairy farm must be scheduled around the milking process.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] Such a milking routine imposes restrictions on the time management and personal life of an individual farmer, as the farmer is committed to milking in the early morning and in the evening for seven days a week, regardless of personal health, family responsibilities or social schedule.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] This time restriction is exacerbated for lone farmers and farm families if extra labour cannot easily or economically be obtained, and is a factor in the decline in small-scale dairy farming.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] Techniques such as once-a-day milking and voluntary milking (see below) have been investigated to reduce these time constraints.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] Automatic teat spraying systems are available, however, there is some debate over the cleaning effectiveness of these.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] Machine milking works by using vacuum pressure to extract milk from cows.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] Specialized machines apply a steady vacuum to the cow's teat, gently sucking out the milk and transferring it to a container.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] Additionally, these machines periodically apply external pressure to the entire teat, which helps maintain proper blood circulation.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] The final manual labour tasks remaining in the milking process were cleaning and inspection of teats and attachment of milking equipment (milking cups) to teats.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] Automatic cleaning and attachment of milking cups is a complex task, requiring accurate detection of teat position and a dexterous mechanical manipulator.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] These tasks have been automated successfully in the voluntary milking system (VMS), or automatic milking system (AMS).
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] Since the 1970s, much research effort has been expended in investigating methods to alleviate time management constraints in conventional dairy farming, culminating in the development of the automated voluntary milking system.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] There is a video of the historical development of the milking robot at Silsoe Research Institute.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] Voluntary milking allows the cow to decide her own milking time and interval, rather than being milked as part of a group at set milking times.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] AMS requires complete automation of the milking process as the cow may elect to be milked at any time.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] The milking unit comprises a milking machine, a teat position sensor (usually a laser), a robotic arm for automatic teat-cup application and removal, and a gate system for controlling cow traffic.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] The cows may be permanently housed in a barn, and spend most of their time resting or feeding in the free-stall area.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] If cows are to be grazed as well, using a selection gate to allow only those cows that have been milked to the outside pastures has been advised by some AMS manufacturers.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] When the cow elects to enter the milking unit (due to highly palatable feed that she finds in the milking box), a cow ID sensor reads an identification tag (transponder) on the cow and passes the cow ID to the control system.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] If the cow has been milked too recently, the automatic gate system sends the cow out of the unit.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] If the cow may be milked, automatic teat cleaning, milking cup application, milking, and teatspraying takes place.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] As an incentive to attend the milking unit, concentrated feedstuffs needs to be fed to the cow in the milking unit.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] The barn may be arranged such that access to the main feeding area can only be obtained by passing the milking unit.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] This layout is referred to as *guided cow traffic*.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] Alternatively, the barn may be set up such that the cow always has access to feed, water, and a comfortable place to lie down, and is only motivated to visit the milking system by the palatable feed available there.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] This is referred to as *free cow traffic*.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] The innovative core of the AMS system is the robotic manipulator in the milking unit.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] This robotic arm automates the tasks of teat cleaning and milking attachment and removes the final elements of manual labour from the milking process.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] Careful design of the robot arm and associated sensors and controls allows robust unsupervised performance, such that the farmer is only required to attend the cows for condition inspection and when a cow has not attended for milking.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] Typical capacity for an AMS is 50–70 cows per milking unit.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] AMS usually achieve milking frequencies between 2 and 3 times per day, so a single milking unit handling 60 cows and milking each cow 3 times per day has a capacity of 7.5 cows per hour.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] This low capacity is convenient for lower-cost design of the robot arm and associated control system, as a window of several minutes is available for each cow and high-speed operation is not required.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] AMS units have been available commercially since the early 1990s, and have proved relatively successful in implementing the voluntary milking method.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] Much of the research and development has taken place in the Netherlands.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] The most farms with AMS are located in the Netherlands, and Denmark.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] A new variation on the theme of robotic milking includes a similar robotic arm system, but coupled with a rotary platform, improving the number of cows that can be handled per robot arm.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] A mobile variation of robotic milking, adapted to tie-stall configuration (stanchion barns), is used in Canada.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] In this configuration, the AMS travels in the centre isle of the barn approaching cows from behind to milk them in their stalls.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] A portable milking machine is an AMS on wheels.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] Portable milking machines have gained popularity with their low cost of installation and ability to take them close to animals who cannot be taken to the barn to milk.
[src:livestock-monitoring/automatic-milking] However they are reliant on manual labour to do the milking and may not be suitable as the only method of milking in large farms.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] A **biosensor** (or **nanobiosensor** in the nanoscale) is an analytical device, used for the detection of a chemical substance, that combines a biological component with a physicochemical detector.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The *sensitive biological element*, e.g. tissue, microorganisms, organelles, cell receptors, enzymes, antibodies, nucleic acids, etc., is a biologically derived material or biomimetic component that interacts with, binds with, or recognizes the analyte under study.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The biologically sensitive elements can also be created by biological engineering.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The biosensor reader device connects with the associated electronics or signal processors that are primarily responsible for the display of the results in a user-friendly way.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] This sometimes accounts for the most expensive part of the sensor device, however it is possible to generate a user friendly display that includes transducer and sensitive element (holographic sensor).
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The readers are usually custom-designed and manufactured to suit the different working principles of biosensors.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] A biosensor typically consists of a bio-receptor (enzyme/antibody/cell/nucleic acid/aptamer), transducer component (semi-conducting material/nanomaterial), and electronic system which includes a signal amplifier, processor & display.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Transducers and electronics can be combined, e.g., in CMOS-based microsensor systems.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The recognition component, often called a bioreceptor, uses biomolecules from organisms or receptors modeled after biological systems to interact with the analyte of interest.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] This interaction is measured by the biotransducer which outputs a measurable signal proportional to the presence of the target analyte in the sample.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The general aim of the design of a biosensor is to enable quick, convenient testing at the point of concern or care where the sample was procured.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] In a biosensor, the bioreceptor is designed to interact with the specific analyte of interest to produce an effect measurable by the transducer.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] High selectivity for the analyte among a matrix of other chemical or biological components is a key requirement of the bioreceptor.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] While the type of biomolecule used can vary widely, biosensors can be classified according to common types of bioreceptor interactions involving: antibody/antigen, enzymes/ligands, nucleic acids/DNA, cellular structures/cells, or biomimetic materials.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] An immunosensor utilizes the very specific binding affinity of antibodies for a specific compound or antigen.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The specific nature of the antibody-antigen interaction is analogous to a lock and key fit in that the antigen will only bind to the antibody if it has the correct conformation.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Binding events result in a physicochemical change that in combination with a tracer, such as fluorescent molecules, enzymes, or radioisotopes, can generate a signal.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] There are limitations with using antibodies in sensors: 1.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The antibody binding capacity is strongly dependent on assay conditions (e.g. pH and temperature), and 2. the antibody-antigen interaction is generally robust, however, binding can be disrupted by chaotropic reagents, organic solvents, or even ultrasonic radiation.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Antibody-antigen interactions can also be used for serological testing, or the detection of circulating antibodies in response to a specific disease.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Importantly, serology tests have become an important part of the global response to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The use of antibodies as the bio-recognition component of biosensors has several drawbacks.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] They have high molecular weights and limited stability, contain essential disulfide bonds and are expensive to produce.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] In one approach to overcome these limitations, recombinant binding fragments (Fab, Fv or scFv) or domains (VH, VHH) of antibodies have been engineered.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] In another approach, small protein scaffolds with favorable biophysical properties have been engineered to generate artificial families of Antigen Binding Proteins (AgBP), capable of specific binding to different target proteins while retaining the favorable properties of the parent molecule.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The elements of the family that specifically bind to a given target antigen, are often selected in vitro by display techniques: phage display, ribosome display, yeast display or mRNA display.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The artificial binding proteins are much smaller than antibodies (usually less than 100 amino-acid residues), have a strong stability, lack disulfide bonds and can be expressed in high yield in reducing cellular environments like the bacterial cytoplasm, contrary to antibodies and their derivatives.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] They are thus especially suitable to create biosensors.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The specific binding capabilities and catalytic activity of enzymes make them popular bioreceptors.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Notably, since enzymes are not consumed in reactions, the biosensor can easily be used continuously.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The catalytic activity of enzymes also allows lower limits of detection compared to common binding techniques.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] However, the sensor's lifetime is limited by the stability of the enzyme.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Antibodies have a high binding constant in excess of 10^8 L/mol, which stands for a nearly irreversible association once the antigen-antibody couple has formed.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] For certain analyte molecules like glucose affinity binding proteins exist that bind their ligand with a high specificity like an antibody, but with a much smaller binding constant on the order of 10^2 to 10^4 L/mol.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The association between analyte and receptor then is of reversible nature and next to the couple between both also their free molecules occur in a measurable concentration.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] In case of glucose, for instance, concanavalin A may function as affinity receptor exhibiting a binding constant of 4x10^2 L/mol.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The use of affinity binding receptors for purposes of biosensing has been proposed by Schultz and Sims in 1979 and was subsequently configured into a fluorescent assay for measuring glucose in the relevant physiological range between 4.4 and 6.1 mmol/L.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The sensor principle has the advantage that it does not consume the analyte in a chemical reaction as occurs in enzymatic assays.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Biosensors employing nucleic acid based receptors can be either based on complementary base pairing interactions referred to as genosensors or specific nucleic acid based antibody mimics (aptamers) as aptasensors.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] In the former, the recognition process is based on the principle of complementary base pairing, adenine:thymine and cytosine:guanine in DNA.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] If the target nucleic acid sequence is known, complementary sequences can be synthesized, labeled, and then immobilized on the sensor.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The hybridization event can be optically detected and presence of target DNA/RNA ascertained.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] In the latter, aptamers generated against the target recognise it via interplay of specific non-covalent interactions and induced fitting.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] These aptamers can be labelled with a fluorophore/metal nanoparticles easily for optical detection or may be employed for label-free electrochemical or cantilever based detection platforms for a wide range of target molecules or complex targets like cells and viruses.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Additionally, aptamers can be combined with nucleic acid enzymes, such as RNA-cleaving DNAzymes, providing both target recognition and signal generation in a single molecule, which shows potential applications in the development of multiplex biosensors.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] It has been proposed that properly optimized integrated optical resonators can be exploited for detecting epigenetic modifications (e.g.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] DNA methylation, histone post-translational modifications) in body fluids from patients affected by cancer or other diseases.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Photonic biosensors with ultra-sensitivity are nowadays being developed at a research level to easily detect cancerous cells within the patient's urine.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Different research projects aim to develop new portable devices that use cheap, environmentally friendly, disposable cartridges that require only simple handling with no need of further processing, washing, or manipulation by expert technicians.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Organelles form separate compartments inside cells and usually perform functions independently.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Different kinds of organelles have various metabolic pathways and contain enzymes to fulfill its function.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Commonly used organelles include lysosome, chloroplast and mitochondria.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The spatial-temporal distribution pattern of calcium is closely related to ubiquitous signaling pathway.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Mitochondria actively participate in the metabolism of calcium ions to control the function and also modulate the calcium related signaling pathways.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Experiments have proved that mitochondria have the ability to respond to high calcium concentrations generated in their proximity by opening the calcium channels.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] In this way, mitochondria can be used to detect the calcium concentration in medium and the detection is very sensitive due to high spatial resolution.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Another application of mitochondria is used for detection of water pollution.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Detergent compounds' toxicity will damage the cell and subcellular structure including mitochondria.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The detergents will cause a swelling effect which could be measured by an absorbance change.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Experiment data shows the change rate is proportional to the detergent concentration, providing a high standard for detection accuracy.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Cells are often used in bioreceptors because they are sensitive to surrounding environment and they can respond to all kinds of stimulants.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Cells tend to attach to the surface so they can be easily immobilized.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Compared to organelles they remain active for longer period and the reproducibility makes them reusable.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] They are commonly used to detect global parameter like stress condition, toxicity and organic derivatives.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] They can also be used to monitor the treatment effect of drugs.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] One application is to use cells to determine herbicides which are main aquatic contaminant.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Microalgae are entrapped on a quartz microfiber and the chlorophyll fluorescence modified by herbicides is collected at the tip of an optical fiber bundle and transmitted to a fluorimeter.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The algae are continuously cultured to get optimized measurement.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Results show that detection limit of certain herbicide can reach sub-ppb concentration level.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Some cells can also be used to monitor the microbial corrosion.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Pseudomonas sp. is isolated from corroded material surface and immobilized on acetylcellulose membrane.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The respiration activity is determined by measuring oxygen consumption.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] There is linear relationship between the current generated and the concentration of sulfuric acid.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The response time is related to the loading of cells and surrounding environments and can be controlled to no more than 5min.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Tissues are used for biosensor for the abundance of enzymes existing.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] There also exist some disadvantages of tissues, like the lack of specificity due to the interference of other enzymes and longer response time due to the transport barrier.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Microbial biosensors exploit the response of bacteria to a given substance.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] For example, arsenic can be detected using the ars operon found in several bacterial taxon.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] An important part of a biosensor is to attach the biological elements (small molecules/protein/cells) to the surface of the sensor (be it metal, polymer, or glass).
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The simplest way is to functionalize the surface in order to coat it with the biological elements.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] This can be done by polylysine, aminosilane, epoxysilane, or nitrocellulose in the case of silicon chips/silica glass.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Subsequently, the bound biological agent may also be fixed—for example, by layer by layer deposition of alternatively charged polymer coatings.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The most commonly used hydrogel is sol-gel, glassy silica generated by polymerization of silicate monomers (added as tetra alkyl orthosilicates, such as TMOS or TEOS) in the presence of the biological elements (along with other stabilizing polymers, such as PEG) in the case of physical entrapment.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Another group of hydrogels, which set under conditions suitable for cells or protein, are acrylate hydrogel, which polymerizes upon radical initiation.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Smart materials that mimic the biological components of a sensor can also be classified as biosensors using only the active or catalytic site or analogous configurations of a biomolecule.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Biosensors can be classified by their biotransducer type.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Electrochemical biosensors combine the exquisite selectivity of biological recognition elements with the high sensitivity and rapid response times of electrochemical transduction.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] To understand their design and application, these systems can be systematically categorized by their electrical measurement techniques and their biorecognition mechanisms.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Electrochemical biosensors are broadly divided into **active techniques** (which force a current or voltage change upon the system to measure a dynamic response) and **passive techniques** (which measure a system at equilibrium or under resting conditions).
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Regardless of the electrical technique used to read out the signal, the specificity of the biosensor depends entirely on its biological layer.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The use of ion channels has been shown to offer highly sensitive detection of target biological molecules.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] By embedding the ion channels in supported or tethered bilayer membranes (t-BLM) attached to a gold electrode, an electrical circuit is created.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Capture molecules such as antibodies can be bound to the ion channel so that the binding of the target molecule controls the ion flow through the channel.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] This results in a measurable change in the electrical conduction which is proportional to the concentration of the target.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] An ion channel switch (ICS) biosensor can be created using gramicidin, a dimeric peptide channel, in a tethered bilayer membrane.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] One peptide of gramicidin, with attached antibody, is mobile and one is fixed.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Breaking the dimer stops the ionic current through the membrane.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The magnitude of the change in electrical signal is greatly increased by separating the membrane from the metal surface using a hydrophilic spacer.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Quantitative detection of an extensive class of target species, including proteins, bacteria, drug and toxins has been demonstrated using different membrane and capture configurations.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The European research project Greensense develops a biosensor to perform quantitative screening of drug-of-abuse such as THC, morphine, and cocaine in saliva and urine.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] A reagentless biosensor can monitor a target analyte in a complex biological mixture without additional reagent.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Therefore, it can function continuously if immobilized on a solid support.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] A fluorescent biosensor reacts to the interaction with its target analyte by a change of its fluorescence properties.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] A Reagentless Fluorescent biosensor (RF biosensor) can be obtained by integrating a biological receptor, which is directed against the target analyte, and a solvatochromic fluorophore, whose emission properties are sensitive to the nature of its local environment, in a single macromolecule.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The fluorophore transduces the recognition event into a measurable optical signal.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The use of extrinsic fluorophores, whose emission properties differ widely from those of the intrinsic fluorophores of proteins, tryptophan and tyrosine, enables one to immediately detect and quantify the analyte in complex biological mixtures.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The integration of the fluorophore must be done in a site where it is sensitive to the binding of the analyte without perturbing the affinity of the receptor.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Antibodies and artificial families of Antigen Binding Proteins (AgBP) are well suited to provide the recognition module of RF biosensors since they can be directed against any antigen (see the paragraph on bioreceptors).
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] A general approach to integrate a solvatochromic fluorophore in an AgBP when the atomic structure of the complex with its antigen is known, and thus transform it into a RF biosensor, has been described.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] A residue of the AgBP is identified in the neighborhood of the antigen in their complex.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] This residue is changed into a cysteine by site-directed mutagenesis.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The fluorophore is chemically coupled to the mutant cysteine.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] When the design is successful, the coupled fluorophore does not prevent the binding of the antigen, this binding shields the fluorophore from the solvent, and it can be detected by a change of fluorescence.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] This strategy is also valid for antibody fragments.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] However, in the absence of specific structural data, other strategies must be applied.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Antibodies and artificial families of AgBPs are constituted by a set of hypervariable (or randomized) residue positions, located in a unique sub-region of the protein, and supported by a constant polypeptide scaffold.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The residues that form the binding site for a given antigen, are selected among the hypervariable residues.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] This approach is also valid for families of antibody fragments.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The RF biosensors that are obtained by the above methods, can function and detect target analytes inside living cells.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Magnetic biosensors utilize paramagnetic or supra-paramagnetic particles, or crystals, to detect biological interactions.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Examples could be coil-inductance, resistance, or other magnetic properties.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] It is common to use magnetic nano or microparticles.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] In the surface of such particles are the bioreceptors, that can be DNA (complementary to a sequence or aptamers) antibodies, or others.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The binding of the bioreceptor will affect some of the magnetic particle properties that can be measured by AC susceptometry, a Hall Effect sensor, a giant magnetoresistance device, or others.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Piezoelectric sensors utilise crystals which undergo an elastic deformation when an electrical potential is applied to them.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] An alternating potential (A.C.) produces a standing wave in the crystal at a characteristic frequency.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] This frequency is highly dependent on the elastic properties of the crystal, such that if a crystal is coated with a biological recognition element the binding of a (large) target analyte to a receptor will produce a change in the resonance frequency, which gives a binding signal.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] In a mode that uses surface acoustic waves (SAW), the sensitivity is greatly increased.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Electrochemiluminescence (ECL) is nowadays a leading technique in biosensors.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Since the excited species are produced with an electrochemical stimulus rather than with a light excitation source, ECL displays improved signal-to-noise ratio compared to photoluminescence, with minimized effects due to light scattering and luminescence background.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The MOSFET invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960, Later, Leland C.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Clark and Champ Lyons invented the first biosensor in 1962.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Biosensor MOSFETs (BioFETs) were later developed, and they have since been widely used to measure physical, chemical, biological and environmental parameters.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The first BioFET was the ion-sensitive field-effect transistor (ISFET), invented by Piet Bergveld for electrochemical and biological applications in 1970. the adsorption FET (ADFET) was patented by P.F.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Cox in 1974, and a hydrogen-sensitive MOSFET was demonstrated by I.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The ISFET is a special type of MOSFET with a gate at a certain distance, and where the metal gate is replaced by an ion-sensitive membrane, electrolyte solution and reference electrode.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The ISFET is widely used in biomedical applications, such as the detection of DNA hybridization, biomarker detection from blood, antibody detection, glucose measurement, pH sensing, and genetic technology.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] By the mid-1980s, other BioFETs had been developed, including the gas sensor FET (GASFET), pressure sensor FET (PRESSFET), chemical field-effect transistor (ChemFET), reference ISFET (REFET), enzyme-modified FET (ENFET) and immunologically modified FET (IMFET).
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] By the early 2000s, BioFETs such as the DNA field-effect transistor (DNAFET), gene-modified FET (GenFET) and cell-potential BioFET (CPFET) had been developed.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The appropriate placement of biosensors depends on their field of application, which may roughly be divided into biotechnology, agriculture, food technology and biomedicine.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] In biotechnology, analysis of the chemical composition of cultivation broth can be conducted in-line, on-line, at-line and off-line.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] As outlined by the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) the sample is not removed from the process stream for in-line sensors, while it is diverted from the manufacturing process for on-line measurements.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] For at-line sensors the sample may be removed and analyzed in close proximity to the process stream.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] An example of the latter is the monitoring of lactose in a dairy processing plant.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Off-line biosensors compare to bioanalytical techniques that are not operating in the field, but in the laboratory.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] These techniques are mainly used in agriculture, food technology and biomedicine.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] In medical applications biosensors are generally categorized as *in vitro* and *in vivo* systems.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] An *in vitro*, biosensor measurement takes place in a test tube, a culture dish, a microtiter plate or elsewhere outside a living organism.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The sensor uses a bioreceptor and transducer as outlined above.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] An example of an *in vitro* biosensor is an enzyme-conductimetric biosensor for blood glucose monitoring.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] There is a challenge to create a biosensor that operates by the principle of point-of-care testing, i.e. at the location where the test is needed.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Development of wearable biosensors is among such studies.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The elimination of lab testing can save time and money.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] An application of a POCT biosensor can be for the testing of HIV in areas where it is difficult for patients to be tested.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] A biosensor can be sent directly to the location and a quick and easy test can be used.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] An *in vivo* biosensor is an implantable device that operates inside the body.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Of course, biosensor implants have to fulfill the strict regulations on sterilization in order to avoid an initial inflammatory response after implantation.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The second concern relates to the long-term biocompatibility, i.e. the unharmful interaction with the body environment during the intended period of use.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] If there is failure, the device must be removed and replaced, causing additional surgery.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] An example for application of an in vivo biosensor would be the insulin monitoring within the body, which is not available yet.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Most advanced biosensor implants have been developed for the continuous monitoring of glucose.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The figure displays a device, for which a Ti casing and a battery as established for cardiovascular implants like pacemakers and defibrillators is used.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Its size is determined by the battery as required for a lifetime of one year.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Measured glucose data will be transmitted wirelessly out of the body within the MICS 402-405 MHz band as approved for medical implants.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Biosensors can also be integrated into mobile phone systems, making them user-friendly and accessible to a large number of users.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] There are many potential applications of biosensors of various types.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] A common example of a commercial biosensor is the blood glucose biosensor, which uses the enzyme glucose oxidase to break blood glucose down.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] In doing so it first oxidizes glucose and uses two electrons to reduce the FAD (a component of the enzyme) to FADH2.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] This in turn is oxidized by the electrode in a number of steps.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The resulting current is a measure of the concentration of glucose.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] In this case, the electrode is the transducer and the enzyme is the biologically active component.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] A canary in a cage, as used by miners to warn of gas, could be considered a biosensor.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Many of today's biosensor applications are similar, in that they use organisms which respond to toxic substances at a much lower concentrations than humans can detect to warn of their presence.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Such devices can be used in environmental monitoring, trace gas detection and in water treatment facilities.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Commercially available glucose monitors rely on amperometric sensing of glucose by means of glucose oxidase, which oxidises glucose producing hydrogen peroxide which is detected by the electrode.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] To overcome the limitation of amperometric sensors, a flurry of research is present into novel sensing methods, such as fluorescent glucose biosensors.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The interferometric reflectance imaging sensor (IRIS) is based on the principles of optical interference and consists of a silicon-silicon oxide substrate, standard optics, and low-powered coherent LEDs.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] When light is illuminated through a low magnification objective onto the layered silicon-silicon oxide substrate, an interferometric signature is produced.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] As biomass, which has a similar index of refraction as silicon oxide, accumulates on the substrate surface, a change in the interferometric signature occurs and the change can be correlated to a quantifiable mass.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] *Daaboul et al.* used IRIS to yield a label-free sensitivity of approximately 19 ng/mL.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] *Ahn et al.* improved the sensitivity of IRIS through a mass tagging technique.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Since initial publication, IRIS has been adapted to perform various functions.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] First, IRIS integrated a fluorescence imaging capability into the interferometric imaging instrument as a potential way to address fluorescence protein microarray variability.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Briefly, the variation in fluorescence microarrays mainly derives from inconsistent protein immobilization on surfaces and may cause misdiagnoses in allergy microarrays.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] To correct for any variation in protein immobilization, data acquired in the fluorescence modality is then normalized by the data acquired in the label-free modality.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] IRIS has also been adapted to perform single nanoparticle counting by simply switching the low magnification objective used for label-free biomass quantification to a higher objective magnification.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] This modality enables size discrimination in complex human biological samples.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] *Monroe et al.* used IRIS to quantify protein levels spiked into human whole blood and serum and determined allergen sensitization in characterized human blood samples using zero sample processing.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Other practical uses of this device include virus and pathogen detection.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] There are several applications of biosensors in food analysis.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] In the food industry, optics coated with antibodies are commonly used to detect pathogens and food toxins.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Commonly, the light system in these biosensors is fluorescence, since this type of optical measurement can greatly amplify the signal.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] These are in widespread use across the food industry.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Biosensors could be used to monitor air, water, and soil pollutants such as pesticides, potentially carcinogenic, mutagenic, and/or toxic substances and endocrine disrupting chemicals.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] For example, bionanotechnologists developed a viable biosensor, ROSALIND 2.0, that can detect levels of diverse water pollutants.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Because ozone filters out harmful ultraviolet radiation, the discovery of holes in the ozone layer of the earth's atmosphere has raised concern about how much ultraviolet light reaches the earth's surface.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Of particular concern are the questions of how deeply into sea water ultraviolet radiation penetrates and how it affects marine organisms, especially plankton (floating microorganisms) and viruses that attack plankton.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Plankton form the base of the marine food chains and are believed to affect our planet's temperature and weather by uptake of CO2 for photosynthesis.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Deneb Karentz, a researcher at the Laboratory of Radio-biology and Environmental Health (University of California, San Francisco) has devised a simple method for measuring ultraviolet penetration and intensity.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Working in the Antarctic Ocean, she submerged to various depths thin plastic bags containing special strains of *E. coli* that are almost totally unable to repair ultraviolet radiation damage to their DNA.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Bacterial death rates in these bags were compared with rates in unexposed control bags of the same organism.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The bacterial "biosensors" revealed constant significant ultraviolet damage at depths of 10 m and frequently at 20 and 30 m.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Karentz plans additional studies of how ultraviolet may affect seasonal plankton blooms (growth spurts) in the oceans.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Metastasis is the spread of cancer from one part of the body to another via either the circulatory system or lymphatic system.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Unlike radiology imaging tests (mammograms), which send forms of energy (x-rays, magnetic fields, etc.) through the body to only take interior pictures, biosensors have the potential to directly test the malignant power of the tumor.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The combination of a biological and detector element allows for a small sample requirement, a compact design, rapid signals, rapid detection, high selectivity and high sensitivity for the analyte being studied.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Compared to the usual radiology imaging tests, biosensors have the advantage of not only finding out how far cancer has spread and checking if treatment is effective but also are cheaper, more efficient (in time, cost and productivity) ways to assess metastaticity in early stages of cancer.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Biological engineering researchers have created oncological biosensors for breast cancer.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Breast cancer is the leading common cancer among women worldwide.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] An example would be a transferrin- quartz crystal microbalance (QCM).
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] As a biosensor, quartz crystal microbalances produce oscillations in the frequency of the crystal's standing wave from an alternating potential to detect nano-gram mass changes.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] These biosensors are specifically designed to interact and have high selectivity for receptors on cell (cancerous and normal) surfaces.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Ideally, this provides a quantitative detection of cells with this receptor per surface area instead of a qualitative picture detection given by mammograms.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Seda Atay, a biotechnology researcher at Hacettepe University, experimentally observed this specificity and selectivity between a QCM and MDA-MB 231 breast cells, MCF 7 cells, and starved MDA-MB 231 cells in vitro.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] With other researchers she devised a method of washing these different metastatic leveled cells over the sensors to measure mass shifts due to different quantities of transferrin receptors.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Particularly, the metastatic power of breast cancer cells can be determined by Quartz crystal microbalances with nanoparticles and transferrin that would potentially attach to transferrin receptors on cancer cell surfaces.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] There is very high selectivity for transferrin receptors because they are over-expressed in cancer cells.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] If cells have high expression of transferrin receptors, which shows their high metastatic power, they have higher affinity and bind more to the QCM that measures the increase in mass.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Depending on the magnitude of the nano-gram mass change, the metastatic power can be determined.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Additionally, in the last years, significant attentions have been focused to detect the biomarkers of lung cancer without biopsy.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] In this regard, biosensors are very attractive and applicable tools for providing rapid, sensitive, specific, stable, cost-effective and non-invasive detections for early lung cancer diagnosis.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Thus, cancer biosensors consisting of specific biorecognition molecules such as antibodies, complementary nucleic acid probes or other immobilized biomolecules on a transducer surface.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] The biorecognition molecules interact specifically with the biomarkers (targets) and the generated biological responses are converted by the transducer into a measurable analytical signal.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Depending on the type of biological response, various transducers are utilized in the fabrication of cancer biosensors such as electrochemical, optical and mass-based transducers.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Biosensors could be used for the detection of pathogenic organisms.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Embedded biosensors for pathogenic signatures – such as of SARS-CoV-2 – that are wearable have been developed – such as face masks with built-in tests.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] New types of biosensor-chips could enable novel methods "such as drone-deployed pathogen sensors actively surveying air or wastewater".
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Protein-binding aptamers could be used for testing for infectious disease pathogens.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p01] Systems of electronic skins (or robot skins) with built-in biosensors (or chemical sensors) and human-machine interfaces may enable wearable as well as remote sensed device- or robotic-sensing of pathogens (as well as of several hazardous materials and tactile perceptions).
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Many optical biosensors are based on the phenomenon of surface plasmon resonance (SPR) techniques.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] This utilises a property of gold and other materials (metals); specifically that a thin layer of gold on a high refractive index glass surface can absorb laser light, producing electron waves (surface plasmons) on the gold surface.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] This occurs only at a specific angle and wavelength of incident light and is highly dependent on the surface of the gold, such that binding of a target analyte to a receptor on the gold surface produces a measurable signal.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Surface plasmon resonance sensors operate using a sensor chip consisting of a plastic cassette supporting a glass plate, one side of which is coated with a microscopic layer of gold.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] This side contacts the optical detection apparatus of the instrument.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] The opposite side is then contacted with a microfluidic flow system.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] The contact with the flow system creates channels across which reagents can be passed in solution.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] This side of the glass sensor chip can be modified in a number of ways, to allow easy attachment of molecules of interest.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Normally it is coated in carboxymethyl dextran or similar compound.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] The refractive index at the flow side of the chip surface has a direct influence on the behavior of the light reflected off the gold side.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Binding to the flow side of the chip has an effect on the refractive index and in this way biological interactions can be measured to a high degree of sensitivity with some sort of energy.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] The refractive index of the medium near the surface changes when biomolecules attach to the surface, and the SPR angle varies as a function of this change.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Light of a fixed wavelength is reflected off the gold side of the chip at the angle of total internal reflection, and detected inside the instrument.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] The angle of incident light is varied in order to match the evanescent wave propagation rate with the propagation rate of the surface plasmon polaritons.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] This induces the evanescent wave to penetrate through the glass plate and some distance into the liquid flowing over the surface.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Other optical biosensors are mainly based on changes in absorbance or fluorescence of an appropriate indicator compound and do not need a total internal reflection geometry.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] For example, a fully operational prototype device detecting casein in milk has been fabricated.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] The device is based on detecting changes in absorption of a gold layer.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] A widely used research tool, the micro-array, can also be considered a biosensor.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Biological biosensors, also known as optogenetic sensors, often incorporate a genetically modified form of a native protein or enzyme.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] The protein is configured to detect a specific analyte and the ensuing signal is read by a detection instrument such as a fluorometer or luminometer.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] An example of a recently developed biosensor is one for detecting cytosolic concentration of the analyte cAMP (cyclic adenosine monophosphate), a second messenger involved in cellular signaling triggered by ligands interacting with receptors on the cell membrane.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Similar systems have been created to study cellular responses to native ligands or xenobiotics (toxins or small molecule inhibitors).
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Such "assays" are commonly used in drug discovery development by pharmaceutical and biotechnology companies.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Most cAMP assays in current use require lysis of the cells prior to measurement of cAMP.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] A live-cell biosensor for cAMP can be used in non-lysed cells with the additional advantage of multiple reads to study the kinetics of receptor response.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Nanobiosensors use an immobilized bioreceptor probe that is selective for target analyte molecules.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Nanomaterials are exquisitely sensitive chemical and biological sensors.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Nanoscale materials demonstrate unique properties.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Their large surface area to volume ratio can achieve rapid and low cost reactions, using a variety of designs.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Other evanescent wave biosensors have been commercialised using waveguides where the propagation constant through the waveguide is changed by the absorption of molecules to the waveguide surface.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] One such example, dual polarisation interferometry uses a buried waveguide as a reference against which the change in propagation constant is measured.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Other configurations such as the Mach–Zehnder have reference arms lithographically defined on a substrate.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Higher levels of integration can be achieved using resonator geometries where the resonant frequency of a ring resonator changes when molecules are absorbed.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Recently, arrays of many different detector molecules have been applied in so called electronic nose devices, where the pattern of response from the detectors is used to fingerprint a substance.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] In the Wasp Hound odor-detector, the mechanical element is a video camera and the biological element is five parasitic wasps who have been conditioned to swarm in response to the presence of a specific chemical.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Current commercial electronic noses, however, do not use biological elements.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] DNA can be the analyte of a biosensor, being detected through specific means, but it can also be used as part of a biosensor or, theoretically, even as a whole biosensor.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Many techniques exist to detect DNA, which is usually a means to detect organisms that have that particular DNA.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] DNA sequences can also be used as described above.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] But more forward-looking approaches exist, where DNA can be synthesized to hold enzymes in a biological, stable gel.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Other applications are the design of aptamers, sequences of DNA that have a specific shape to bind a desired molecule.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] The most innovative processes use DNA origami for this, creating sequences that fold in a predictable structure that is useful for detection.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Scientists have built prototype sensors to detect DNA of animals from sucked in air, "airborne eDNA".
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] "Nanoantennas" made out of DNA – a novel type of nano-scale optical antenna – can be attached to proteins and produce a signal via fluorescence when these perform their biological functions, in particular for distinct conformational changes.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Graphene is a two-dimensional carbon-based substance with superior optical, electrical, mechanical, thermal, and mechanical properties.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] The ability to absorb and immobilize a variety of proteins, particularly some with carbon ring structures, has proven graphene to be an excellent candidate as a biosensor transducer.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] As a result, various graphene-based biosensors have been explored and developed in recent times.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Graphene has been employed as a biosensor in various formats especially electrochemical sensors and field effect transistors.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] Amongst them graphene field effect transistors (GFETs) especially have shown excellent performance as rapid point of care (PoC) diagnostics as observed through a surge in number of research articles reporting COVID-19 diagnostics using GFETs.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] They have been reported to have some of the lowest limit of detection whilst also having a rapid turn around time of a few seconds along with multiplexing abilities.
[src:livestock-monitoring/biosensor-p02] These capabilities allow for immediate disease detection especially in cases with overlapping symptoms which are hard to distinguish at the outset, thus allowing for better patient outcomes especially in resource strained medical settings.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] An **ear tag** is a plastic or metal object used for identification of livestock and wildlife.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] If the ear tag uses Radio Frequency Identification Device (RFID) technology it is referred to as an **electronic ear tag**.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Electronic ear tags conform to international standards ISO 11784 and ISO 11785 working at 134.2 kHz, as well as ISO/IEC 18000-6C operating in the UHF spectrum.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] There are other non-standard systems such as Destron working at 125 kHz.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Each of these except the metal type may carry a RFID chip, which normally carries an electronic version of the same identification number.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] An ear tag usually carries an Animal Identification Number (AIN) or code for the animal, or for its herd, flock, or pack.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Non electronic ear tags may be simply handwritten for the convenience of the farmer (these are known as "management tags").
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Alternatively this identification number (ID) may be assigned by an organisation which is a not-for-profit organisation owned by cattle, sheep, goat and pig producers and funded by a levy on livestock sales with government input; an example is the Meat and Livestock Association (MLA) of Australia.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Electronic tags may also show other information about the animal, including other related identification numbers; such as the Property Identification Code (PIC) for the properties the animals have been located.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Depending on jurisdiction, the movement of certain species of livestock (primarily cattle, goats, sheep and pigs) must be recorded in the online database within 24 hours of the movement; and include the PICs of the properties the animals are travelling between.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] The National Livestock Identification System (NLIS) of Australia regulations require that all cattle be fitted with a RFID device in the form of an ear tag or rumen bolus (a cylindrical object placed in the rumen) before movement from the property and that the movement be reported to the NLIS.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] However, if animals are tagged for internal purposes in a herd or farm, IDs need not be unique in larger scales.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] The NLIS now also requires sheep and goats to use an ear tag that has the Property Identification Code inscribed on it.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] These ear tags and boluses are complemented by transport documents supplied by vendors that are used for identification and tracking.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] A similar system is used for cattle in the European Union (EU), each bovine animal having a passport document and tag in each ear carrying the same number.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Pigs are required in the EU to carry in one of the ears a tag with the number of the herd of birth, as well as with the numbers of any other herds the pig was kept with for more than 30 days; tattooing may be used as a replacement.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] An ear tag can be applied with an ear tag applicator, however there are also specially designed tags that can be applied by hand.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Depending on the purpose of the tagging, an animal may be tagged on one ear or both.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] There may be requirements for the placement of ear tags, and care must be taken to ensure they are not placed too close to the edge of the ear pinnae; which may leave the tag vulnerable to being ripped out accidentally.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] If there exists a national animal identification programme in a country, animals may be tagged on both ears for the sake of increased security and effectiveness, or as a legal requirement.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] If animals are tagged for private purposes, usually one ear is tagged.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Australian sheep and goats are required to have visually readable ear tags printed with a Property Identification Code (PIC).
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] They are complemented by movement documents supplied by consignors that are used for identification and tracking.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Very small ear tags are available for laboratory animals such as mice and rats.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] They are usually sold with a device that pierces the animal's ear and installs the tag at the same time.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Lab animals can also be identified by other methods such as ear punching or marking (also used for livestock; see below), implanted RFID tags (mice are too small to wear an ear tag containing an RFID chip), and dye.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Livestock ear tags were developed in 1799 under the direction of Sir Joseph Banks, President of the Royal Society, for identification of Merino sheep in the flock established for King George III.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Matthew Boulton designed and produced the first batch of sheep eartags, and produced subsequent batches, modified according to suggestions received from Banks.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Ear tags were incorporated as breed identification in the United States with the forming of the ***International Ohio Improved Chester Association*** as early as 1895, and stipulated in the Articles of Incorporation, as an association animal and breed identification, of the improved Chester White.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Although ear tags were developed in Canada as early as 1913 as a means to identify cattle when testing for tuberculosis, the significant increase of use of ear tags appeared with the outbreak of BSE in UK.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Today, ear tags in a variety of designs are used throughout the world on many species of animal to ensure traceability, to help prevent theft and to control disease outbreaks.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] The first ear tags were primarily steel with nickel plating.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] After World War II, larger, flag-like, plastic tags were developed in the United States.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Designed to be visible from a distance, these were applied by cutting a slit in the ear and slipping the arrow-shaped head of the tag through it so that the flag would hang from the ear.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] In 1953, the first two-piece, self-piercing plastic ear tag was developed and patented.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] This tag, which combined the easy application of metal tags with the visibility and colour options of plastic tags, also limited the transfer of blood-borne diseases between animals during the application process.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Some cattle ear tags contain chemicals to repel insects, such as buffalo flies, horseflies, etc.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Metal ear tags are used to identify the date of regulation shearing of stud and show sheep.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Today, a large number of manufacturers are in competition for the identification of world livestock population.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Government asked farmers to use EID or Electronic Identification ear tags on all their cattle.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] This request was part of the National Animal Identification System (NAIS) spurred by the discovery of the first case of mad cow disease in the United States.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] The United States Department of Agriculture maintains a list of manufacturers approved to sell ear tags in the USA.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] The International Committee for Animal Recording (ICAR) controls the issue electronic tag numbers under ISO regulation 11784.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] The National Livestock Identification System (NLIS) is Australia's system for tracing cattle, sheep and goats from birth to slaughter.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] In Canada, the Health of Animals Regulations require approved ear tags on all bison, cattle and sheep that leave the farm of origin, except that a bovine may be moved, without a tag, from the farm of origin to a tagging site.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] RFID (radio frequency identification) tags are used for cattle in Canada and metal as well as RFID tags have been in use for sheep.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Mandatory RFID tagging of sheep in Canada (which was previously scheduled to take effect January 1, 2013) will be deferred to some later date.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Pigs, cattle and sheep are frequently earmarked with pliers that notch registered owner and/or age marks into the ear.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Mares on large horse breeding farms have a plastic tag attached to a neck strap for identification; which preserves their ears free of notches.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Dairy cows are sometimes identified with ratchet fastened plastic anklets fitted on the pastern for ready inspection during milking; however, NLIS requirements apply to cattle – including both dairy and beef animals.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] More commonly coloured electrical tape is used as short-term ankle identifiers for dairy animals to identify when one teat should not be milked for any reason.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] Laboratory rodents are often marked with ear tags, ear notches or implantable microchips.
[src:livestock-monitoring/ear-tag] The National Livestock Identification System (NLIS) Australia, formerly used cattle tail tags for property identification and hormone usage declaration.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] An **electronic identification** ("**eID**") is a digital solution for proof of identity of citizens or organizations.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] They can be used to view to access benefits or services provided by government authorities, banks or other companies, for mobile payments, etc.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Apart from online authentication and login, many electronic identity services also give users the option to sign electronic documents with a digital signature.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] One form of eID is an **electronic identification card** (**eIC**), which is a physical identity card that can be used for online and offline personal identification or authentication.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The eIC is a smart card in ID-1 format of a regular bank card, with identity information printed on the surface (such as personal details and a photograph) and in an embedded RFID microchip, similar to that in biometric passports.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The chip stores the information printed on the card (such as the holder's name and date of birth) and the holder's photo(s).
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Several photos may be taken from different angles along with different facial expressions, thus allowing the biometric facial recognition systems to measure and analyze the overall structure, shape and proportions of the face.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] It may also store the holder's fingerprints.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The card may be used for online authentication, such as for age verification or for e-government applications.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] An electronic signature, provided by a private company, may also be stored on the chip.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Germany, Uruguay and previously Finland have accepted government issued physical eICs.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Norway, Sweden and Finland accept bank-issued eIDs (also known as BankID) for identification by government authorities.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] There are also an increasing number of countries applying electronic identification for voting (enrollment, issuing voter ID cards, voter identification and authentication, etc.), including those countries using biometric voter registration.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] According to the EU electronic identification and trust services (eIDAS) Regulation, described as a pan-European login system, all organizations delivering public digital services in an EU member state shall accept electronic identification from all EU member states from 29 September 2018.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Austria has initially issued eIDs ("Bürgerkarte") via its national health insurance card (eCard), but has later introduced an app-based solution ("Handy-Signatur").
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Electronic signatures were deemed equivalent to handwritten signatures since January 2000.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] As of 5 December 2023, the Handy-Signatur and the Bürgerkarte (Citizen Card) have been upgraded and replaced by "ID Austria", which offers enhanced digital identification and authentication capabilities.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] More than 2 Million people are enrolled in ID Austria.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] It interconnects with eIDAS systems from other EU Member States.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] It is widely used for government online services, but also increasingly by the private sector.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Belgium has been issuing eIDs since 2003, and all identity cards issued since 2004 have been electronic, replacing the previous plastic card.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] At home, the users can use their electronic IDs to log into specific websites (such as Tax-on-web, allowing them to fill in their tax form online).
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] When other software (such as an Internet Browser) attempts to read the eID, the users are asked for confirmation for this action, and potentially even for their PIN.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Other applications include signing emails with the user's eID certificate private key.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Giving the public key to your recipients allows them to verify your identity.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Although legally Belgian citizens only have to carry an ID from the age of 12, as of March 2009, a "Kids ID" has been introduced for children below this age, on a strictly voluntary basis.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] This ID, beside containing the usual information, also holds a contact number that people, or the child themselves, can call when they, for example, are in danger or had an accident.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The card can be used for electronic identification after the age of six, and it does not contain a signing certificate as minors cannot sign a legally binding document.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] An important goal of the Kids-ID card is to allow children to join "youth-only" chat sites, using their eID to gain entrance.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] These sites would essentially block any users above a certain age from gaining access to the chat sessions, effectively blocking out potential pedophiles.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Bulgaria introduced a limited scale proof-of-concept of electronic identity cards, called ЕИК (Eлектронна карта за идентичност), in 2013.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Croatia introduced its electronic identity cards, called *e-osobna iskaznica*, on 8 June 2015.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Electronic identities in Denmark, issued by banks and the government jointly, is named MitID.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The former eID, NemID, was deprecated as of October 2023.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] MitID authentication allows larger payments in MobilePay - a service used by more than half of the population as of 2017.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The Estonian ID card, issued since 2002, is also used for authentication for Estonia's Internet-based voting system.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] In February 2007, Estonia was the first country to allow for electronic voting for parliamentary elections.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Over 30,000 voters participated in the country's e-election.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] At end of 2014 Estonia extended the Estonian ID Card to non-residents.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The target of the project is to reach 10 million residents by 2025, which is 8 times more than the Estonian population of 1.3 million.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The Finnish electronic ID was first issued to citizens on 1 December 1999.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Electronic identities in Finland are issued by banks.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] They make it possible to log into Finnish authorities, universities and banks, and to make larger payments using the MobilePay mobile payment service.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The *mobiilivarmenne* is utilizing the mobile phone SIM card for authentication, and is financed by a fee to the mobile network operator for each authentication.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] since 2021, France has rolled out a physical chip enabled ID card (Carte Nationale d'Identité or CNI as a short) with a ISO ID-1 profile.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The mobile application France Identité provides eID mobile features such as authentication on the identity federation portal (France Connect) as well as multiple factor authentication thru another portal (France Connect +) to access multiple administration and non administration websites in France.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] It also serves as a digital wallet to store personal credentials (driving licences, car documents, etc) and it can generate a document to prove identity in a secure way without sending a copy of the documents (Justificatif d'identité à usage unique).
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Previous ID cards are being phased out and new cards are being provided free.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Germany introduced its electronic identity cards, called Personalausweis, in 2010.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Greece introduced a new generation of electronic identity cards (Δελτίο Ταυτότητας νέου τύπου) starting in 2023, replacing the older paper-based identity cards.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The new cards include an embedded contactless electronic chip containing the holder’s personal and biometric data, and are compliant with ICAO and EU security standards.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The electronic Greek ID card is intended for secure identification and authentication, both in physical and digital contexts, and is designed to support access to e-government services.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] In parallel, Greece has developed a digital identity framework through the government platform gov.gr, including mobile-based digital credentials via Gov.gr Wallet, which can be used for identification in selected public and private sector services.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The rollout of the new electronic identity cards is being carried out gradually nationwide.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] In Iceland, electronic IDs (Icelandic: *Rafræn skilríki*) are extensively used by the public and private sector today and were first introduced in 2008.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The most widely used version today is on a mobile phone - with the authentication key held on a SIM card.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] In Iceland 95% of the eligible population (13 years or older) has an active eID, including 75% of over 75s.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Icelandic eID holders used their eID more than 20 times a month in 2021.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Each time they need to identify, verify or sign something online, a prompt via flash SMS is initiated and the PIN code is validated.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Today this system is used by all banks, government services (island.is portal), healthcare, eductation, document signing and over 300 private companies using for customer page logins (linked to the Icelandic ID no.).
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Since the only thing to remember is one's PIN code and their phone, it is very prevalent, and works as a sort of single-sign-on service.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] They are administered by Auðkenni hf., which was initially created by a consortium of banks but is now owned by the government.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The first form of the system in 2008 was a special smartcard with an EMV chip, paired with a smartcard reader on the client's computer.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The smartcard was first introduced in late 2008 for employees of government departments, large companies and the healthcare system.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] It was rolled out to all departments and companies handling sensitive data.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] It was also possible to store one's eID on a debit card.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] In November 2013 the SIM card implementation for mobile phones was introduced, which led to a much quicker take-up of eIDs due to its ease of use.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] By 2014, 40% of Icelanders were using eIDs.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Italy introduced its electronic identity cards, called *Carta d'Identità Elettronica* (in Italy identified with the acronym *CIE*), to replace the paper-based ID card in Italy.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Since 4 July 2016, Italy is in the process of renewing all ID cards to electronic ID cards.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Since 12 February 2014, Malta is in the process of renewing all ID cards to electronic ID cards.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Electronic identities in Netherlands are called DigiD and Netherlands is currently developing an eID scheme.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Electronic identities in Norway issued by banks are called BankID (different than Sweden's BankID).
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] They make it possible to log into Norwegian authorities, universities and banks, and to make larger payments using the Vipps mobile payment service, used by more than half of the population as of 2017.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Electronic identity cards in Spain are called DNIe and have been issued since 2006.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] SwissID, developed by SwissSign, is a certified digital ID in Switzerland offered since 2017 (2010–17 as SuisseID).
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] As a base for a new *Federal Act on Electronic Identification Services (e-ID Act)*, an eID-concept had been developed by the authorities, yet experts criticized its technology part.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The law was accepted by the Swiss parliament on 29 September 2019.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] It would have updated current legislation and would have continued to allow private companies or public organizations to issue eIDs if certified by a new federal authority.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] However, an optional referendum called for a public vote on this issue in the weeks until Sunday, 7 March 2021.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The vote resulted in 35.6% Yes and 64.4% No, rejecting the proposed new law.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] In 2025, a revised version of the law was approved by the public with the eID becoming available in 2026.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] SwissSign might develop the SwissID further, to make it compatible with future E-ID regulations.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The most widespread electronic identification in Sweden is issued by banks and called BankID (different than Norwegian BankID).
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The BankID may be in the form of a certificate file on disk, on card or on smart phones.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The latter (Swedish *mobile BankID* service) was used by 84 percent of the Swedish population in 2019.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] A Mobile BankID login does not require a fee since the service is provided by banks rather than mobile operators.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] It can be used both for authentication within various apps and web services on the same smart phone, and also for web pages on other devices.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] It also supports fingerprint and face recognition authentication on compatible iOS and Android devices.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Electronic IDs are used for secure web login to Swedish authorities, banks, health centers (allowing people to see their medical records and prescriptions and book doctors visits), and companies such as pharmacies.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Mobile BankID also allows the Swish mobile payment service, utilized by 78 percent of the Swedish population in 2019, at first mainly for payments between individuals.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] BankID was previously used for university applications and admissions, but this was prohibited by Swedbank since universities utilized the system for distribution of their own student logins.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Increasingly, BankID is used as an added security for signing contracts.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The adoption of eIDs varies per EU Member State.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] While some countries mainly rely on government eID systems, others have dominant private or public-private systems, like eIDs managed by banks.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The table below provides an overview over eID adoption in various countries.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Afghanistan issued its first electronic ID (e-ID) card on 3 May 2018.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Afghan President Ashraf Ghani was the first to receive the card.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Afghan President was accompanied by First Lady Rula Ghani, his VP, Head of Afghan Senate, Head of Afghan Parliament, Chief Justice and other senior government officials, and they also received their cards.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] As of January 2021, approximately 1.7 million Afghan citizens have obtained their e-ID cards.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Costa Rica plans to introduce facial recognition data into its national identification card.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Guatemala introduced its electronic identity card called DPI (Documento Personal de Identificación) in August 2010.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Indonesia introduced its electronic identity cards, called e-KTP.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Indonesian electronic ID was trialed in six areas in 2009 and launched nationwide in 2011.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Electronic identity cards in Israel have been issued since July 2013.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Kazakhstan introduced its electronic identity cards in 2009.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Mauritius has had electronic identity cards since 2013.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] General Multi-purpose Electronic Identity Cards are issued by the National Identity Management Commission (NIMC), a Federal Government agency under the Presidency.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The NeID Card complies with ICAO standard 9303, ISO standard 7816–4., as well as GVCP for the MasterCard-supported payment applet.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] NIMC plans to issue 50m multilayer-polycarbonate cards, the first set being contact only, but also dual-interface with DESFire Emulation in the near future.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Pakistan officially began its nationwide Computerized National Identity Card (CNIC) distribution in 2002, with over 89.5 x CNICs issued by 2012.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] In October 2012, the National Database and Registration Authority (NADRA) introduced the smart national identity card (SNIC), which contains a data chip and 36 security features.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The SNIC complies with ICAO standard 9303 and ISO standard 7816–4.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The SNIC can be used for both offline and online identification, voting, pension disbursement, social and financial inclusion programmes and other services.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] NADRA aims to replace all 89.5 million CNICs with SNICs by 2020.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Serbia has its first trustful and reliable electronic identity since June 2019.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The first reliable service provider is The Office for IT and eGovernment, through which citizens and residents of Serbia can access services on eGovernment Portal and eHealth portal.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The electronic identification offers two levels of security, first basic level with authentication of only user name and password, and medium level of two-factor of authentication.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] In Turkey the e-Government (e-Devlet) Gateway is a largely scaled Internet site that provides access to all public services from a single point.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The purpose of the Gateway is to present public services to the citizens, enterprises and public institutions effectively and efficiently with information and communication technologies.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Uruguay has had electronic identity cards since 2015.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] The Uruguayan eID has a private key that allows to digitally sign documents, and has the user fingerprint stored in order to allow to verify the identity.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] It is also a valid travel document in some South American countries.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] As of 2017 the old laminated ID coexists with the new eID.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] Electronic identification can also be attributed to the manufacturing sector, where the technology of electronic identification is transferred to individual parts or components within a manufacturing facility in order to track, and identify these parts to enhance manufacturing efficiency.
[src:livestock-monitoring/electronic-identification] This can also be referred to location detection technologies within the Fourth Industrial Revolution.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] The breeding, maintenance, slaughter and general subjugation of livestock, called *animal husbandry*, is a part of modern agriculture and has been practiced in many cultures since humanity's transition to farming from hunter-gatherer lifestyles.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Animal husbandry practices have varied widely across cultures and periods.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] They continue to play a major economic and cultural role in numerous communities.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Livestock farming practices have largely shifted to intensive animal farming.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Such farming increases the yield of the various commercial outputs, but also impairs animal welfare, the environment, and public health.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] In particular, beef, dairy and sheep are an outsized source of greenhouse gas emissions from agriculture.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] The word *livestock* was first used between 1650 and 1660, as a compound word combining the words "live" and "stock".
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] In some periods, "cattle" and "livestock" have been used interchangeably.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Over the 19th century, the meaning of livestock and cattle shifted, leading to the modern meaning of cattle referring to domesticated bovines, whilst livestock is used in a wider sense.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] United States federal legislation defines the term to make specified agricultural commodities eligible or ineligible for a program or activity.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] For example, the Livestock Mandatory Reporting Act of 1999 (P.L.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Horses are considered livestock in the United States.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] The USDA classifies pork, veal (meat of young cows, usually 5–8 months old), beef, and lamb (mutton) as livestock, and all livestock as red meat.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Poultry and fish are not included in the category.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] The latter is likely because fish products are not governed by the USDA, but by the FDA.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Animal-rearing originated during the cultural transition to settled farming communities from hunter-gatherer lifestyles.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Animals are domesticated when their breeding and living conditions are controlled by humans.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Over time, the collective behaviour, lifecycle and physiology of livestock have changed radically.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Many modern farmed animals are unsuited to life in the natural world.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Dogs were domesticated early; dogs appear in Europe and the Far East from about 15,000 years ago.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Goats and sheep were domesticated in multiple events sometime between 11,000 and 5,000 years ago in Southwest Asia.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Pigs were domesticated by 8,500 BC in the Near East and 6,000 BC in China.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Domestication of horses dates to around 4,000 BC.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Cattle have been domesticated since approximately 10,500 years ago.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Chickens and other poultry may have been domesticated around 7,000 BC.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] The term "livestock" is indistinct and may be defined narrowly or broadly.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Broadly, livestock refers to any population of animals kept by humans for a useful, commercial purpose.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Traditionally, animal husbandry was part of the subsistence farmer's way of life, producing not only the food needed by the family but also the fuel, fertiliser, clothing, transport and draught power.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Killing the animal for food was a secondary consideration, and wherever possible their products, such as wool, eggs, milk and blood (by the Maasai) were harvested while the animal was still alive.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] In the traditional system of transhumance, humans and livestock moved seasonally between fixed summer and winter pastures; in montane regions the summer pasture was up in the mountains, the winter pasture in the valleys.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Similar cattle stations are found in South America, Australia and other places with large areas of land and low rainfall.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] In between these two extremes are semi-intensive, often family-run farms where livestock graze outside for much of the year, silage or hay is made to cover the times of year when the grass stops growing, and fertiliser, feed and other inputs are bought onto the farm from outside.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Livestock farmers have often dealt with natural world animals' predation and theft by rustlers.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] In North America, animals such as gray wolves, grizzly bears, cougars, and coyotes are sometimes considered a threat to livestock.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] In Eurasia and Africa, predators include wolves, leopards, tigers, lions, dholes, Asiatic black bears, crocodiles, spotted hyenas, and other carnivores.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] In South America, feral dogs, jaguars, anacondas, and spectacled bears are threats to livestock.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] In Australia, dingoes, foxes, and wedge-tailed eagles are common predators, with an additional threat from domestic dogs who may kill in response to a hunting instinct, leaving the carcass uneaten.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Good husbandry, proper feeding, and hygiene are the main contributors to animal health on farms, bringing economic benefits through maximised production.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] In the European Union, when farmers treat the animals, they are required to follow the guidelines for treatment and to record the treatments given.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Animals are susceptible to a number of diseases and conditions that may affect their health.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Some, like classical swine fever and scrapie are specific to one population of animals, while others, like foot-and-mouth disease affect all cloven-hoofed animals.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Where the condition is serious, governments impose regulations on import and export, on the movement of livestock, quarantine restrictions and the reporting of suspected cases.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] At one time, antibiotics were routinely added to certain compound foodstuffs to promote growth, but this is now considered poor practice in many countries because of the risk that it may lead to antibiotic resistance.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Animals living under intensive conditions are particularly prone to internal and external parasites; increasing numbers of sea lice are affecting farmed salmon in Scotland.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] According to the Special Report on Climate Change and Land, livestock diseases are expected to get worse as climate change increases temperature and precipitation variability.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Since many livestock are herd animals, they were historically driven to market "on the hoof" to a town or other central location.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] The method is still used in some parts of the world.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Truck transport is now common in developed countries.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Local and regional livestock auctions and specialized agricultural markets facilitate trade in livestock.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] In Canada at the Cargill slaughterhouse in High River, Alberta, 2,000 workers process 4,500 cattle per day, or more than one-third of Canada's capacity.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] It closed when some of its workers became infected with coronavirus disease 2019.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] The Cargill plant together with the JBS plant in Brooks, Alberta and the Harmony Beef plant in Balzac, Alberta represent fully three-quarters of the Canadian beef supply.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] In other areas, livestock may be bought and sold in a bazaar or wet market, such as may be found in many parts of Central Asia.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] In non-Western countries, providing access to markets has encouraged farmers to invest in livestock, with the result being improved livelihoods.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] For example, the International Crops Research Institute for the Semi-Arid Tropics (ICRISAT) has worked in Zimbabwe to help farmers make their most of their livestock herds.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] In stock shows, farmers bring their best livestock to compete with one another.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Humans and livestock make up more than 90% of the biomass of all terrestrial vertebrates, and almost as much as all insects combined.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] The value of global livestock production in 2013 has been estimated at 883 billion dollars, (constant 2005–2006 dollars).
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Livestock provide a variety of food and non-food products; the latter include leather, wool, pharmaceuticals, bone products, industrial protein, and fats.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] For many abattoirs, very little animal biomass may be wasted at slaughter.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Even intestinal contents removed at slaughter may be recovered for use as fertilizer.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Livestock manure helps maintain the fertility of grazing lands.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Manure is commonly collected from barns and feeding areas to fertilize cropland due to its nutrient rich content, however, can pose some biosecurity and health risks.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] In some places, animal manure is used as fuel, either directly (as in some non-Western countries), or indirectly (as a source of methane for heating or for generating electricity).
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] In regions where machine power is limited, some classes of livestock are used as draft stock, not only for tillage and other on-farm use, but also for transport of people and goods.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] In 1997, livestock provided energy for between an estimated 25 and 64% of cultivation energy in the world's irrigated systems, and that 300 million draft animals were used globally in small-scale agriculture.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Although livestock production serves as a source of income, it can provide additional economic values for rural families, often serving as a major contributor to food security and economic security.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Livestock can serve as insurance against risk and is an economic buffer (of income and food supply) in some regions and some economies (e.g., during some African droughts).
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] However, its use as a buffer may sometimes be limited where alternatives are present, which may reflect strategic maintenance of insurance in addition to a desire to retain productive assets.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Even for some farmers in Western nations, livestock can serve as a kind of insurance.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Some crop growers may produce livestock as a strategy for diversification of their income sources, to reduce risks related to weather, markets and other factors.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Many studies have found evidence of the social, as well as economic, importance of livestock in non-Western countries and in regions of rural poverty, and such evidence is not confined to pastoral and nomadic societies.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Social values in developed countries can also be considerable.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] In the US, profit tends to rank low among motivations for involvement in livestock ranching.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Instead, family, tradition and a desired way of life tend to be major motivators for ranch purchase, and ranchers "historically have been willing to accept low returns from livestock production".
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] It is responsible for somewhere between 20 and 33% of the fresh water usage in the world, and livestock, and the production of feed for them, occupy about a third of Earth's ice-free land.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Livestock production is a contributing factor in species extinction, desertification, and habitat destruction.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Meat is considered one of the prime factors contributing to the current sixth mass extinction.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Animal agriculture contributes to species extinction in various ways.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] The newest report released by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) states that between the 1970s and 2000s agricultural emission increases were directly linked to an increase in livestock.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] The population growth of livestock (including cattle, buffalo, sheep, and goats) is done with the intention of increasing animal production, but in turn increases emissions.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] The IPCC has estimated that agriculture (including not only livestock, but also food crop, biofuel and other production) accounted for about 10 to 12 percent of global anthropogenic greenhouse gas emissions (expressed as 100-year carbon dioxide equivalents) in 2005 and in 2010.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Cattle produce some 79 million tons of methane per day.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Live westock enteric methane account 30% of the overall methane emissions of the planet.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Livestock are responsible for 34% of all human-related emissions of nitrous oxide, through feed production and manure..Best production practices are estimated to be able to reduce livestock emissions by 30%.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] There are numerous interlinked effects of climate change on livestock rearing.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] This activity is both heavily affected by and a substantial driver of anthropogenic climate change due to its greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] As of 2011, some 400 million people relied on livestock in some way to secure their livelihood.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] The commercial value of this sector is estimated as close to $1 trillion.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] As an outright end to human consumption of meat and animal products is not currently considered a realistic goal, any comprehensive adaptation to effects of climate change must also consider livestock.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] The observed adverse impacts on livestock production include increased heat stress in all but the coldest nations.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] This causes both mass animal mortality during heatwaves, and the sublethal impacts, such as lower quantity of quality of products like milk, greater vulnerability to conditions like lameness or even impaired reproduction.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Another impact concerns reduced quantity or quality of animal feed, whether due to drought or as a secondary impact of CO2 fertilization effect.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Difficulties with growing feed could reduce worldwide livestock headcounts by 7–10% by midcentury.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Animal parasites and vector-borne diseases are also spreading further than they had before, and the data indicating this is frequently of superior quality to one used to estimate impacts on the spread of human pathogens.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] While some areas which currently support livestock animals are expected to avoid "extreme heat stress" even with high warming at the end of the century, others may stop being suitable as early as midcentury.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] On the other hand, Japan, the United States and nations in Europe are considered the least vulnerable.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] This is as much a product of pre-existing differences in human development index and other measures of national resilience and widely varying importance of pastoralism to the national diet as it is an outcome of direct impacts of climate on each country.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Proposed adaptations to climate change in livestock production include improved cooling at animal shelters and changes to animal feed, though they are often costly or have only limited effects.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] At the same time, livestock produces the majority of greenhouse gas emissions from agriculture and demands around 30% of agricultural fresh water needs, while only supplying 18% of the global calorie intake.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Animal-derived food plays a larger role in meeting human protein needs, yet is still a minority of supply at 39%, with crops providing the rest.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Consequently, plans for limiting global warming to lower levels like 1.5 °C (2.7 °F) or 2 °C (3.6 °F) assume animal-derived food will play a lower role in the global diets relative to now.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] As such, net zero transition plans now involve limits on total livestock headcounts (including reductions of already disproportionately large stocks in countries like Ireland), and there have been calls for phasing out subsidies currently offered to livestock farmers in many places worldwide.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Animal ethics is a branch of ethics that examines human-animal relationships and the moral consideration of non-animals.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Debates within the field address the moral implications of using animals for human consumption and the responsibilities humans have toward livestock.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] It is estimated that worldwide, 74% of livestock are raised in factory farms, characterized by densely confined animals.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Consumers are typically against intensive livestock farming when surveyed.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] A majority are unaware of routine controversial practices such as break trimming, separation of calves from their mothers and gas chamber slaughter.
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Three quarters of US adults surveyed believed the animal products they consumed came from animals that were treated "humanely".
[src:livestock-monitoring/livestock] Believing that livestock farming is cruel was cited as the most common reason for becoming vegan or vegetarian throughout the 2010s.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] PLF technologies include cameras, microphones, and other sensors for tracking livestock, as well as accompanying computer software.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] The data recorded can be either quantitative or qualitative, and/or address sustainability.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] PLF involves the monitoring of animals, or the use of measurements on the animals, using signal analysis algorithms and statistical analysis.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] These techniques are applied in part with the goal of regaining an advantage of older, smaller-scale farming, namely detailed knowledge of individual animals.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Before large farms became the norm, most farmers had an intimate knowledge of their livestock.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Moreover, a farmer could typically trace an animal's pedigree and retain other important characteristics.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Each animal was approached as an individual.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Since then farms have multiplied in scale, with highly automated processes for feeding and other tasks.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Consequently, farmers are forced to work with many more animals to make their living out of livestock farming and work with average values per group.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Variety has become an impediment to increasing economies of scale.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Using information technology, farmers can record the attributes of each animal, such as pedigree, age, reproduction, growth, health, feed conversion, killing out percentage (carcass weight as a percentage of its live weight) and meat quality.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Animal welfare, infection, aggression, weight, feed and water intake are variables that can be monitored by PLF.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Culling can be done on the basis of reproduction values, in addition to killing out percentage, meat quality, and health.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] The result of incorporating this technology into large-scale farming is a potentially significantly higher reproduction outcome, with each newborn also potentially contributing to a higher meat value.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Selecting the "right" ingredients can have a positive effect on the environment pollution.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] It has been shown that optimizing the feed this can reduce nitrogen and phosphorus found in the excrement of pigs.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] In automatic milking, a robotic milker can be used for precision management of dairy cattle.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] The main advantages are time savings, greater production, a record of valuable information, and diversion of abnormal milk.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] An automatic feeder is a tool used to provide feed to cattle.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] It is composed of a robot (either on a rail system or self-propelled) that will feed the cattle at designated times.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] The robot mixes the feed ration and will deliver a programmed amount.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Activity collars gather biometric data from animals.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Some wearable devices help farmers with estrous detection, as well as other adverse health events or conditions.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Inline milk sensors help farmers identify variation of components in the milk.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Some sensors are relatively simple technologies that measure properties such as electrical conductivity, and others use automated sampling and reagents to provide a different measure to inform management decisions.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Radio Frequency IDentification (commonly known as RFID or EID) is applied in cattle, pigs, sheep, goats, deer and other types of livestock for individual identification.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] There is currently a growing trend of RFID or EID becoming mandatory for certain species.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] For example, Australia has made EID compulsory for cattle, as has New Zealand for deer, and the European Union for sheep and goats.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] EID makes identification of individual animals much less error-prone.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] RFID enhances traceability, but it also provides other benefits such as reproduction tracking (pedigree, progeny, and productivity), automatic weighing, and drafting.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Smart cattle ear tags constantly gather behavioural and biometric data from cattle, allowing managers to see the exact animals that need more attention regarding their health.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Smart ear tagging has been shown to be effective in identifying illness earlier and more accurately than traditional visual monitoring.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Automated weight detection cameras can be used to calculate the pig's weight without a scale.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] These cameras can have an accuracy of less than 1.5 kilograms.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] In the swine industry, the presence of respiratory problems must be closely monitored.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] There are multiple pathogens that can cause infection; enzootic pneumonia is one of the most common respiratory diseases in pigs caused by *Mycoplasma hyopneumoniae* and other bacteria.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Thermal stress is connected to reduced performance, illness, and mortality.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Depending on geographical location, and the types of animals will require different heating or ventilation systems.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] Broilers, laying hens, and piglets like to be kept warm.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] In the poultry industry, unfavourable climate conditions increase the chances of behavioural, respiratory, and digestive disorders in the birds.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] The development of quantitative methods for livestock production includes mathematical modelling based in plant-herbivore or predator-prey models to forecast and optimise meat production.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] An example is the *Predator-Prey Grassland Livestock Model* (PPGL) to address the dynamics of the combined grass-animals system as a predator-prey dynamical system.
[src:livestock-monitoring/precision-livestock-farming] This PPGL model has been used to simulate the effect of forage deficiency on the farm's economic performance.
